  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 27:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μόλις τε παραλεγ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αὐτὴν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": “and with difficulty coasting along it,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Crete on the southern side—with difficulty because under the same conditions as in their journey along the coast of Asia Minor (Breusing) (this is better than to refer ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αὐτήν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Σαλμώνην",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and render to work past, to weather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Grimm-Thayer); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "παραλέγομαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "oram legere",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Diodorus Siculus, Strabo.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Καλοὺς Λιμένας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": a small bay two miles east of Cape Matala, in modern Greek, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Λιμεῶνας Καλούς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", J. Smith, p. 82, and Appendix, p. 251 ff., 4th edition; not mentioned, however, elsewhere. This harbour would afford them shelter for a time, for west of Cape Matala the land trends suddenly to the north, and they would have been again exposed to the north-westerly winds; see further for a description of the place Findlay’s ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Mediterranean Directory",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 66, quoted by Breusing and Goerne, who also have no doubt that the place is identical with that mentioned by St. Luke (see also Wendt, 1898 and 1899).—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Λασαία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see critical note; like the Fair Havens not mentioned by name in any ancient writer. but since 1856 it may be fairly said that its identification has been established with a place some four miles to the east of Fair Havens, or rather the ruins of a place to which the name Lasea was still given, see J. Smith, 4th edition, p. 82, and p. 268 (Appendix); Alford, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Proleg.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to Acts, p. 27. If Lasea was one of “the (ninety or) hundred towns of Crete,” and one of the smaller amongst them, it ceases to be strange that no precise mention of it should occur in ancient writers (Grimm).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and hardly passing it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] “Hardly” is in the original the same word which was rendered “scarce” in the previous verse. Read (with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "R. V.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") “with difficulty coasting along it.” The verb represents the voyage as made by keeping close in to the southern shores of the island.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "came unto a place",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i.e. on the coast of Crete. The Gk. gives (as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "R. V.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") “a certain place.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "which is called The fair havens",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "R. V.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " “called Fair Havens.” This place, though mentioned nowhere else in literature, yet is known by the same name still. It is on the south of Crete, four or five miles east of Cape Matala, which is the largest headland on that side of the island.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Lasea",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This city has also been identified very recently. Its ruins were discovered in 1856, a few miles east of Fair Havens. See Smith’s ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Voyage and Shipwreck of St Paul",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", App. iii. pp. 262, 263.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 27:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Μόλις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hardly",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Construed with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἤλθομεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "we came",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καλοὺς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Perhaps this epithet was given by antiphrasis; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 27:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “the haven was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "not commodious",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ":” as the name, Pontus Euxinus.[148]—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Λασαία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") So the best MSS.: two have ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἄλασσα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": whence the Latin Vulg. has ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thalassa",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".[149] The word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "civitas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", immediately preceding (in the Vulg.), may have caused the prefixing of the letter ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "t",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from its third syllable.[150] We assign more weight to the Asiatic MSS. than to the African, when the question is concerning the names of places. Crete ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "is said",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἑκατόμπολις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as is remarked in the Periplus of Scylax. Among the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hundred",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " towns, how many are unknown in our days?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[148] Which means ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hospitable to strangers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", whereas it was a sea notoriously ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "inhospitable",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἄξεινος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and inclement: but was called the former from a superstitious feeling to avoid a bad omen.—E. and T.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[149] Rec. Text and Tisch. read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Λασαία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with the sanction of the two Syr. Versions alone of the oldest authorities. B and Memph. read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Λασέα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". A has ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἄλασσα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and so Lachm. Vulg. has Thalassa, and in other MSS. Thassala.—E. and T.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[150] Before ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἄλασσα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which would favour the reading of A: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Alassa, Talassa, Thalassa",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—E. and T.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "- With difficulty coasting along it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "hardly passing it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "we came",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "came",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a certain place called",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "place which is called",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Fair",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the Fair",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "With difficulty coasting along it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "παραλεγόμενοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", only here and ver. 13. It is a nautical phrase, meaning to sail alongside of the coast. In Latin ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "legere",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " has the same meaning. The difficulty arose from their being under the lee of the island, which sheltered them from the north-west wind, but left them without any motive power. However, they managed to get as far as Fair Havens, where they anchored in the roadstead so called, near to an obscure and otherwise unknown town called Lasea, possibly the same as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Lasos",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", mentioned by Pliny as one of the inland cities of Crete ('Nat. Hist.,' 4. 12:20), or as Elaea (ibid.). Acts 27:8",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]